{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":4349,"record_hash":"sha256:2b2002c0e9bc9a116d2f8f26839f390ae7fa8bfe0e05d42816194e305a8badbc","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:41:25.180Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"status\":{\"[REDACTED:entropy]\":{\"completed\":\"Found 3 POC-sized privacy/security risks.\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P1] Base64 secrets with slashes bypass redaction\\\" body=\\\"`/` is part of the candidate alphabet, but any candidate with two or more slashes is treated as `pathish` and skipped. That means base64-like credentials with slashes, including AWS-style secret keys, can have entropy above the threshold yet remain unredacted.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=145 end=146 priority=1 confidence=0.93}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P2] Hex credentials are not caught\\\" body=\\\"Pure hex strings cannot exceed 4 bits of Shannon entropy per character, while the threshold is `> 4.0`; additionally, 40- and 64-character hex strings are always treated as common hashes. This preserves commit/SHA data, but also lets common hex-encoded API, webhook, and HMAC secrets pass through unchanged.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=98 end=118 priority=2 confidence=0.9}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P3] Entropy-only matching can erase useful slugs\\\" body=\\\"The candidate alphabet includes `/`, `_`, and `-`, so ordinary long branch names or transcript identifiers such as `[REDACTED:entropy]` can cross the entropy threshold and be replaced wholesale. That is likely acceptable only if the POC docs are explicit that redaction is lossy; otherwise this can remove important transcript context.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=102 end=106 priority=3 confidence=0.78}\\n\\nI also checked the privacy notes: they do clearly frame this as local-only POC storage with a “small high-entropy redaction guard,” so I would avoid claiming stronger protection until those false negatives are tightened. Targeted validation run: `cargo test -p but-agentlog redaction --lib` passed.\"}},\"timed_out\":false}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:41:25.180Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}